abstract = {Coherent many-body quantum dynamics lies at the heart of quantum simulation and quantum computation. Both require coherent evolution in the exponentially large Hilbert space of an interacting many-body system [1, 2]. To date, trapped ions have defined the state of the art in terms of achievable coherence times in interacting spin chains [3–6]. Here, we establish an alternative platform by reporting on the observation of coherent, fully interaction-driven quantum revivals of the magnetization in Rydberg-dressed Ising spin chains of atoms trapped in an optical lattice. We identify partial many-body revivals at up to about ten times the characteristic time scale set by the interactions. At the same time, single-site-resolved correlation measurements link the magnetization dynamics with inter-spin correlations appearing at different distances during the evolution. These results mark an enabling step towards the implementation of Rydberg atom based quantum annealers [7], quantum simulations of higher dimensional complex magnetic Hamiltonians [8, 9], and itinerant long-range interacting quantum matter [10–12].},
